Obesity Level Classification Using Physical Condition and Lifestyle Habit Predictors

Julian Widjaja, Miku Yamada, Philip Loewen, Subhan Chiluwal

2022-04-08

Introduction

Obesity is defined as a disease involving excessive body fat and can significantly impact the health of an individual. In comparison to people with normal weight, those with obesity are associated with a higher risk of negative health conditions such as Type 2 diabetes, heart disease and cancer (Nguyen, 2010). Dietary changes, lifestyle habits, and treatment can positively influence the obesity level of an individual (Trivedi, 2014). In our data analysis, we would like to classify the obesity level category for an individual using physical condition and lifestyle habits, in order for them to gain knowledge of their current health and to help inform future lifestyle choices.

Question: What is the obesity level category (underweight, normal, Overweight I, Overweight II, Obesity I, Obesity II, Obesity III) of a new observation predicted by physical condition and eating habits?

The dataset used includes data on the estimated obesity levels of individuals from Mexico, Peru and Columbia using eating habits and physical conditions. The dataset classifies an individual into one of the seven obesity level classes (outlined above) and contains 17 attributes with 2111 records. Some of the data was directly collected from web users, while others were synthetically generated.

In our project, we will focus on the following predictors to build our classification model. Key terms of the predictors are defined below:

-FAF is Physical Activity Frequency

-CH20 is Consumption of Water Daily

-TUE is Time Using Technology Devices

-Weight

Building our model

Splitting data into training and testing data

We split our data into training and testing data in order to build our K-nearest neighbor classifier and be able to further evaluate the accuracy of our classifier.

The training set will be used to build the classifier and the test set will then be used to test the accuracy of our classifier.

set.seed(255)

obesity_split <- initial_split(obesity, prop = 0.75, strata = NObeyesdad)
obesity_train <- training(obesity_split)
obesity_test <- testing(obesity_split)


The reason we summarize and visualize the training data only is because we build our model using the training data, not the testing data.

Finding the best K to use

To find the best K for our classifier, we are going to follow these few steps: 1. We will generate five different train/validation splits of our overall training data 2. Create the appropriate model specification and standardized recipe for tuning the classifier 3. We choose to test 20 values of K (1 - 20) 4. Create our workflow to find the accuracy for each value in a range of K values

set.seed(255) 

min_vfold <- vfold_cv(obesity_train, v = 5, strata = NObeyesdad)

min_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_fun = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) %>%
            set_engine("kknn") %>%
            set_mode("classification")

obesity_recipe <- recipe(NObeyesdad ~ Weight + FAF + CH2O + TUE, data = obesity_train) %>%
                step_scale(all_predictors()) %>%
                step_center(all_predictors())  

k_vals <- tibble(neighbors = seq(from = 1, to = 20, by = 1))

k_data <- workflow() %>%
        add_recipe(obesity_recipe) %>%
        add_model(min_spec) %>%
        tune_grid(resamples = min_vfold, grid = k_vals) %>%
        collect_metrics() %>%
        filter(.metric == "accuracy")

print("Table 4")
## [1] "Table 4"
kable(head(k_data))
neighbors .metric .estimator mean n std_err .config
1 accuracy multiclass 0.7388297 5 0.0099930 Preprocessor1_Model01
2 accuracy multiclass 0.7381968 5 0.0090567 Preprocessor1_Model02
3 accuracy multiclass 0.7165827 5 0.0077056 Preprocessor1_Model03
4 accuracy multiclass 0.7122002 5 0.0094003 Preprocessor1_Model04
5 accuracy multiclass 0.6943513 5 0.0135944 Preprocessor1_Model05
6 accuracy multiclass 0.6880339 5 0.0139453 Preprocessor1_Model06

In table 4, we can see the mean accuracy of our first six values of neighbors (K). To ease things, we are going to plot the accuracy versus K to decide which number of neighbors is the best.

k_plot <- ggplot(k_data, aes(x = neighbors, y = mean)) +
            geom_line() +
            geom_point() +
            labs(x = "Neighbors", 
                 y = "Mean accuracy", 
                 title = "Graph showing the mean accuracy for each neighbor level", 
                 subtitle = "Figure 3") +
            theme(text = element_text(size = 10))

k_plot

Figure 3 shows the mean accuracy for each of the k-nearest neighbor values. To determine the k-value we would like to use for our KNN classification, we chose the value of ~3 from figure 3 as we can see that the accuracy was the highest (72.5%).

k_min <- k_data %>%
            arrange(desc(mean)) %>%
            slice(1) %>%
            pull(neighbors)

k_min
## [1] 1

Using our K to create the model

Now that we have the best value for K, we use this K to build our classifier: 1. We create a new model specification using our new K 2. Build our classifier by combining our new model spec and recipe into a workflow and fit it with the training data

set.seed(255)

obesity_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_fun = "rectangular", neighbors = k_min) %>%
                set_engine("kknn") %>%
                set_mode("classification")


obesity_fit <- workflow() %>%
        add_recipe(obesity_recipe) %>%
        add_model(obesity_spec) %>%
        fit(obesity_train)

Testing the model

Test our K-nearest neighbors classifier object’s accuracy by using it to predict our testing data

set.seed(255)
predictions <- predict(obesity_fit, obesity_test) %>%
                bind_cols(obesity_test)

Figure 4 depicts a visualization of the confusion matrix for the classifier in a heatmap form. This confusion matrix is a table showing the prediction accuracy per class of our classifer via predicted and true labels (the lighter the color blue, the higher the prediction accuracy per class). For example, the new observation that we classified for this project was classified in the Overweight Level II obesity class. The confusion matrix suggests that there is a 43.06% chance that we predicted the obesity level correctly, i.e. our new observation is indeed Overweight Level II. The visualization is one of the important tools we used to critically analyze the performance of our classifier.

Discussion

Outcomes:

Through our K-nearest neighbors classification process, the new observation was classified as the obesity level category of Overweight Level II using the predictors of weight, physical activity frequency, consumption of water daily, and time using technology devices. This classification was obtained using a k-nearest neighbors value of 3 which can be seen from Figure 3. When observing the accuracy of our classifier, we can estimate that our obesity level category classification has around a 72.0% prediction accuracy for this project. Observing the heatmap of the confusion matrix in Figure 4, we can further see that the newly classified observation that was predicted as Overweight Level 2 has a 43.06% chance of being classified correctly in this category.

Expectation:

The classification of the new observation as Overweight Level 2 was what we expected to find based on the characteristics of the new observation. The new observation we created has a higher weight with fairly low physical activity and low water consumption. So, we expect them to be over normal weight (Overweight) but not into the classes of obesity.

Impacts:

Classifying the new observation into an obese level category can help the individual know their level of obesity and its relationship with their lifestyle. By knowing which habits are negatively affecting their health, individuals may then make various changes in their current lifestyle in order to live a healthier life. In this case, the new observation has been classified as an obesity level category of Overweight Level II. This classification can impact the individual’s lifestyle decisions such as deciding to eat healthier or exercise more frequently to reduce their obesity level category and try to fall in the normal category. These classifications can help these individuals live longer and healthier by raising awareness of their weight-health.

Future Questions:

In the future, we could look into possible diseases in relation to different stages of obesity (eg. What is the relation between obesity and heart diseases?) Another interesting future question would be to look into categorizing the new observations with other predictors that are not given from this dataset that are also relevant to obesity/weight levels (eg. family history/genetic factors/wealth). Related to this, it would be interesting to perform this study with all given dataset predictors rather than just the four used for the purpose of this study.
